sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects when an attacker or tool disables the  Windows Defender service (WinDefend) via the registry
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Ján Trencanský, frack113, AlertIQ, Nasreddine Bencherchali

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Disable Windows Event Logging Via Registry
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects tampering with the "Enabled" registry key in order to disable Windows logging of a Windows event channel

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Change Winevt Channel Access Permission Via Registry
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects tampering with the "ChannelAccess" registry key in order to change access to Windows event channel.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Access To Browser Credential Files By Uncommon Application
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects file access requests to browser credential stores by uncommon processes.
Could indicate potential attempt of credential stealing.
Requires heavy baselining before usage
Detects unusual processes accessing desktop.ini, which can be leveraged to alter how Explorer displays a folder's content (i.e. renaming files) without changing them on disk.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: DNS Server Discovery Via LDAP Query
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects DNS server discovery via LDAP query requests from uncommon applications

Detects execution of the builtin "del"/"erase" commands in order to delete files.
Adversaries may delete files left behind by the actions of their intrusion activity.
Malware, tools, or other non-native files dropped or created on a system by an adversary may leave traces to indicate to what was done within a network and how.
Removal of these files can occur during an intrusion, or as part of a post-intrusion process to minimize the adversary's footprint.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Load Of RstrtMgr.DLL By An Uncommon Process
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the load of RstrtMgr DLL (Restart Manager) by an uncommon process.
This library has been used during ransomware campaigns to kill processes that would prevent file encryption by locking them (e.g. Conti ransomware, Cactus ransomware). It has also recently been seen used by the BiBi wiper for Windows.
It could also be used for anti-analysis purposes by shut downing specific processes.

packers.PEiD: UPX v0.89.6 - v1.02 / v1.05 -v1.24 -> Markus & Laszlo [overlay]

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factors were that it has known exploits and it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This sample is a packed malicious loader/backdoor. It uses UPX packing and dynamic API resolution via function name hashing (sub_405aec) to obscure its true capabilities and hide its Import Address Table (IAT). The binary contains custom string decryption routines (sub_401240 and sub_418c34) and low-level NT system call wrappers for process manipulation. Concrete malicious behaviors include process hollowing/injection (sub_4104b4) using NtWriteVirtualMemory and NtProtectVirtualMemory wrappers, and C2 communication capabilities (sub_40cfcc) that construct HTTP/HTTPS requests targeting ports 80 and 443. It also performs extensive system environment checks and process enumeration (sub_40ac28) to ensure it is running in a target environment.
